brewery.brewery_description: We are brewer-owned and consider everyone who walks through our doors to be family. We are inspired by the desire to celebrate the end of a long day with great beer and even better friends. We use only the highest quality ingredients to brew an exceptional selection of beers that honor tradition, history, and innovation in the industry. We are here for the locals and out of towners, the working people and the party people, the brewers and the consumers. At Steam Bell Beer Works, our beer is for everyone.

beer.beer_description: Milk Stout brewed with whole vanilla beans, rum soaked oak chips and Ironclad Coffee Co. Brazilian coffee.
A light-bodied saison that is sessionable with slight notes of pepper and spice
A flavorful American IPA restrained on the bitterness, but bursting with delicious American hop character.
Fermented over chocolate and locally sourced pecans.
Belgian tripel fermented with maple syrup and aged on whole vanilla beans

Milk stout brewed with orange peel, nutmeg, whole vanilla beans and cinnamon. 

This one reminds us of a deliciously refreshing (grown up) milkshake which is where it gets it's name. As legend has it, our 1st President loved ice cream so much that he spent a whopping $200 on this vice during the summer of 1790.

Packed with extra plenty amounts of hibiscus and locally sourced cucumbers, this Gose blends into a deliciously refreshing taste reminiscent of watermelon candy. Pink Himalayan salt brings in a hint of salinity, rounding out this beers flavor while keeping it true to style.
Our collaboration with Blue Beer Cider. A light-bodied Belgian brewed with blackberries and raspberries
Brewed with Copper Fox Distillery's peach wood smoked malt. Then fermented with 200 pounds of hand cut fresh peaches from Century Farm in Crozet, VA.
A strong ale brewed with honey and applewood cherry smoked malt
Light bodied and slightly spiced saison fermented with fresh Virginia blueberries and fresh basil.

Burger Bach Collaboration. A light bodied pale ale brewed with taro root and all New Zeleand hops, then fermented over fresh kiwi. Light fruit notes backed by a bold punch from dry hopping with Nelson Sauvin hops.

Scotch Ale fermented with fresh cranberries. This beer is the perfect compliment to the gorgeous fall weather we're currently experiencing: full bodied, slightly sweet and a bit tart. Berkeley Hundred is named for the estate in Virginia where the first Thanksgiving was held almost 400 years ago.

Belgian Ale fermented over tart cherries and toasted almonds. This beer was created in collaboration with One Belle Bakery LLC with the almonds being used to represent One Belle's best selling amaretto cake. 

During the month of October, a portion of all proceeds from this beer will be donated to the VCU Massey Cancer Center for breast cancer research.
Brewed especially for Hops in the Park! This easy drinking ale uses all Virginia grown malts, hops grown at Henricus Historical Park, a locally foraged yeast, and Nelson County sorghum syrup.
5% ABV rye saison Brett fermented in white wine barrels
A beer produced to benefit the VCU Massey Cancer Center this light saison has been brewed with rose hips and pink peppercorns.
Belgian Amber Ale brewed with Virginia Sweet Potatoes, Sorghum Syrup and aged on Toasted Pumpkin Seeds.
The liège brewed with white sangria fruit
The first in our series of barrel aged beers. An American Wild Ale aged in charred oak barrels for 6 months
Pale Ale aged with Brettanomyces in oak charred barrels for six months dry hopped with Citra.
Solely dry hopped with Citra hops, imparting strong notes of grapefruit and orange marmalade.
Saison brewed with beets and turmeric.

A Sour Ale conditioned on Raspberries and conditioned with mixed sour culture. Deuce Deuce was aged for 18 months in red wine barrels that impart slight hints of oak. Brettanomyces add complex, funky notes of ripe raspberry and apricot with sharp acidity.
